<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>

<activity xml:id="act-problemasDeComparacion" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"> 

<title>[@@@@@@@@@]</title>

<statement>
  <p>[@@@@@@@@@]</p>
</statement>

<solution>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ol>
      <li><p>The caterpillar crawled farther. Sample response:</p><ul>
<li>A third is larger than an eighth, so 2 thirds is larger than 2 eighths.</li>
<li>
<m>\frac{2}{3} &gt; \frac{2}{8}</m> (or <m>\frac{2}{8} &lt; \frac{2}{3}</m>)</li>
</ul>
      </li>
      <li><p>They are the same length. Sample response:</p><ul>
<li>Three thirds is equivalent to 1, so 12 thirds is equivalent to 4.</li>
<li>
<m>\frac{12}{3} = 4</m> (or <m>4 = \frac{12}{3}</m>)</li>
</ul>
      </li>
      <li><p>The ant crawled farther. Sample response:</p><ul>
<li>A number line showing that the point for 5 eighths is to the right of the point for 3 eighths</li>
<li>
<m>\frac{3}{8} &lt; \frac{5}{8}</m> (or <m>\frac{5}{8} &gt; \frac{3}{8}</m>)</li>
</ul>
      </li>
      <li><p>The frog jumped a longer distance. Sample response:</p><ul>
<li>Sixths are larger than eighths, so 5 sixths is larger than 5 eighths.</li>
<li>
<m>\frac{5}{6} &gt; \frac{5}{8}</m> (or <m>\frac{5}{8} &lt; \frac{5}{6}</m>)</li>
</ul>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>


